photo.title: Belt of Venus

description._content:
If you like to be chained up & beaten by a leather clad dominatrix, or even just enjoy a good spanking - you could be forgiven for feeling a frisson of excitement at the mention of Belt of Venus - after all Venus is the goddess of love.
 Unfortunately I discovered this week that Belt of Venus is a term for something much more humdrum - the pink arch seen above the blue band of the Earth's shadow as witnessed here behind Coit tower.
 Had to do this long panorama of evening light on the buildings on Nob hill - didn't feel I could cut out Coit tower or the Art Deco buildings on Fisherman's wharf?
 Wanted to wait for a blue hour shot but was getting that look of impatience from my wife that says it's dinner time.

Thanks to Everyone who took the trouble to view, comment or fave.

description._content:
As I crossed the street, this view was just too good to pass.  So I took a quick snap before the traffic hit me.  

Columbus Avenue the main artery of North Beach, the famous tourist spot.  Colloquially called Little Italy, it had and still has large population of Italian heritage.  North Beach was once a beach, until the land northeast of it was reclaimed and new piers were built on it (yes, Pier 39 and vicinity).  So don't look for beach here, the beach no longer exist.  But instead, visit some colorful Italian restaurants and walk around the famous Washington Square Park with Sts. Peter and Paul Cathedral next to it.

That cathedral in view is another beautiful house of god.  The national shrine is named after San Francis of Assisi, the patron saint of animals and of course, the namesake of San Francisco.

photo.title: Go Ahead and Shoot Me

description._content: Go Ahead – Shoot Me The Critique: An icon stands tall against a sumptuous sky showing off intricate details – sharing the soft color palette – as she soars with the clouds. Nice perspective – a little different than usual with sort of an over the shoulder look - creates nice impact. Triangles are always attention grabbing, adding strength, and this lovely building is all about triangles – she’s a pyramid. Lovely light shows off her patterned windows and facade. The Transamerica pyramid says quite simply – San Francisco. What I have learned. Shoot icons when they insist. I see her often but on this day she said – shoot me. So I did. description._content:
Driving into San Francisco and even finding a nice parking spot on Russian Hill had been surprisingly easy.  It was getting OUT of the city that turned into a nightmare!  

First, I could not find my way out of Russian Hill!  It was an endless maze of four-way stops across a geometric grid of residential streets.  I went around and around, trying to find some kind of major street that would take me towards the freeway to cross the Bay Bridge to Oakland.  Somehow I ended up going down a steep street and saw THIS in front of me!  There was even a small driveway where I could pull over for a second to get a shot through the windshield!  On the left is the base of the Transamerica Pyramid.  This is at Montgomery & Vallejo.

description._content: The Transamerica Pyramid is, at 260 m, the tallest building in San Francisco. It was designed by William Pereira and built from 1969 to 1972, to serve as the headquarters of the Transamerica Corporation. The unique pyramidal shape is due to Transamerica's CEO, who wanted to minimize the amount of shade cast on the streets below. The bright colour of the exterior is due to a coating of crushed quartz. Transamerica has since moved its headquarters to Baltimore, Maryland; the pyramid's office space is now leased out to various companies.

The Transamerica Pyramid, is the tallest skyscraper in San Francisco. At 260 m (853 ft), on completion in 1972 it was the eighth tallest building in the world.

Although the tower is no longer Transamerica Corporation headquarters, it is still associated with the company and is depicted in the company's logo. The building is evocative of San Francisco and has become one of the many symbols of the city.

photo.title: The "Transamerica Pyramid"

description._content:
The Transamerica Pyramid is the tallest skyscraper in the San Francisco skyline.  Commissioned by Transamerica CEO John R. Beckett in 1969, it was designed by architect William Pereira and built by Hathaway Dinwiddie Construction Company.  It was the eighth tallest building in the world.  Built on the site of the historic "Montgomery Block", it has a structural height of 853 ft. and has 48 floors of retail and office space.

The Transamerica Pyramid replaced the "Montgomery Block", San Francisco's first fireproof and earthquake resistant building erected in 1853.  Upon construction, this former four-story structure became the tallest building of its time west of the Mississippi River.

photo.title: Painted Ladies

description._content:
Alamo Square
WHERE HISTORY MEETS HIPSTER............
Alamo Square is one of most popular & photographed location in San Francisco. This spot gives you Unique Architectural beauty San Francisco is known for.These beautiful historical Victorian Houses to foreground and background of San Francisco Urban skyline provides stunning contrast.
These Victorian Houses also known as “Painted Ladies” and “Postcard Rows”.
Painted Ladies refers to Victorian and Edwardian houses painted in three or more colors that enhance or embellish their architectural details.
This particular row of colorful houses (also sometimes called The Six Sisters) was built between 1892 and So Not only are they perfectly beautiful but these houses are rich with the history and the culture of the city.
Also they withstood famous 1906 San Francisco Earthquake.
These colorful houses have become famous as a symbol of San Francisco architecture. They have been featured in numerous television shows and movies that are set in San Francisco. Last one I saw Five Years Engagement (Emily Blunt , Jason Seagull )
On Christmas Eve decided to take a break actually(even if we have a break officially smile emoticon and do some photographing some Holiday Lights. But its been raining on and off in the bay area for past few days and its been chilly and windy…..
But my experience tells me that often during clearing of the rain(or the storm as they say it here) you will see spectacular sunrise/sunset. So I was praying for rain to stop for a brief.
Although thankfully rain stopped in the evening of Christmas Eve but I didn’t get that spectacular Sunset but because of rain and cloudy skies I got some dark blue sky during sunset. Also it was full moon day so the sky was lit up whenever moon peek through clouds provided interesting lights. Oh yes they again didn’t turn on that transamerica beacon during sunset ugh.. but they did turn it on later in the evening.
So once again "Happy Holidays Everyone!!"

photo.title: Legends of the City

description._content: Over the past few years I have made more than a half dozen visits to this spot for the classical view of the San Francisco skyline under the Bay Bridge. An iconic and breathtaking scene it never ceases to amaze with its beauty and the constantly changing skyline. In lieu of recent events at Yerba Buena Island I decided to make another attempt at this shot but to finally get the burning sky that has constantly eluded me. Having slept through a crazy sunrise Aaron and I did not want to miss another potential light show. With skies looking promising, we departed for San Francisco. Upon arriving at we ran into none other than Jeff and Tung. Despite then vacillating on where to shoot, we all ended up making the trek to the under the Bay Bridge spot. The clouds were already looking amazing and we crossed our finger that they would not depart our frame by sunset. Luckily the clouds moved slowly and the sky ignited into popcorn-like pink and red burn. This evening was by far the best sunset I have gotten at this spot and I can finally put this one to rest. This shot is a “timelapse” blend of 2 shots: one for the sunset and one for the city lights taken roughly 15 minutes later. Hope you enjoy and may the holiday season commence! photo.title: Thread_The_Needle_1

description._content:
Happy Holidays !! 
Holiday Lights of San Francisco !!
Holidays period started officially from last week. Its that time of the year when you find Christmas tree and light decorations everywhere, every thing looks merry, bright and sparkling specially in big cities like San Francisco.
In fact its ideal time for photographing city light. Heres my first few photographs of this year holiday lights. I’ll be adding few more from other locations in San Francisco over coming weekends. 
Threading the Needle :- 
Framing of transamerica building through window of north tower of golden gate bridge. Photogs also call this Threading the needle as transamerica pyramid which looks like needle  which fits into opening of north tower of Golden Gate bridge. 
You can get this shot only from one spot where transamerica building and north tower of golden gate bridge are perfectly aligned. And that spot is very popular amongst photogs so either you need to go very early or you need to be lucky in order to get that spot. 
Also this spot is on …hawk hill which often gets very windy and cold. Also beacon on that transamerica pyramid is lit only during holidays period and on special occasions i.e. 4th July etc. Also during this winter holiday period you will have more chances of not to  get those foggy conditions, which San Francisco more famous for ….. :)
So timeframe for this shot is very limited. Also when I took this shot first time couple of years back, that beacon is used to get turned on late in the evening, so one used to loose blue hour if you are photographing this shot. But this time thankfully they turned on that beacon just before sunset and luckily I got this spot for half an hour all to my self. May be because of windy n cold conditions nobody showed up during sunset.

photo.title: Red Tail Patriots flying past Transamerica Pyramid during San Francisco air show 151010-142333 C4V

description._content: There is always lots of preliminary activity of the weekend airshows featuring the U.S. Navy and Marine Corps Blue Angels team aerobatic flight demonstrations. The hour before the Blue Angels scheduled starting time, on the second weekend of October 2015, belonged to the Patriots Jet Team, the largest civilian aerobatic formation team that performs in air shows across western North America. This is an image of five of the six Red Tailed Patriots jets about to fly behind the Transamerica Pyramid from our vantage point from the 22nd story of a residential building on Gough Street near the corner of Geary Boulevard about two miles away from this action. It was a wonderful place to capture images of the airshows, allowing us a seemingly level or even superior viewpoint of the airships in motion. Thank you, Anna, for inviting us to your lovely home during this event. We enjoyed a wonderful meal and, those of us who wished, got a birds eye view of the airshows. One other fact about this photo is that, to date, the Transamerica Pyramid is the tallest skyscraper in San Francisco - tall enough for the speeding jets to use as a prop.

photo.title: Transamerica Pyramid and flag on Top of the Mark Hopkins Hotel six blocks from each other 151010-150645 C4

description._content: This is a telephoto view of the Transamerica Pyramid with the Top of the Mark Hopkins Hotel with flag in the foreground taken from the 22nd floor of a residential building on Gough Street near the corner of Geary Boulevard. Shots using long focal length lenses can make things appear much closer than they really are. In this case the flag atop the Mark Hopkins Hotel is about 9 blocks away (as the crow flies) and the point of the Transamerica Pyramid is more than a mile from our high rise vantage point.

photo.title: Blue Angels passing Transamerica Pyramid 151010-151503 C4

description._content: The Transamerica Pyramid Center is the tallest skyscraper in San Francisco and is one of the most recognizable landmarks of the downtown skyline. We had a good view of the pyramid building from our 22nd floor perch on Gough Street near Geary Boulevard on October 10, 2015 while visiting with friends on the Saturday of the Patriots of Canada and Blue Angels Navy flying teams. This last photo of the top portion of the pyramid building shows four of the Blue Angels banking right after they had passed behind the pointed top. Optical illusion made them seem much closer to the building than they actually were. Glad I was able to keep the jets in the frame as they were moving at a pretty good clip.
